Here is the full **testsmells.org 19-smell** audit of `UserRepositoryIntegrationTests.cs`, with integration-test calibration applied.

---

## Summary Dashboard

| Severity | Smell Count | Affected Tests |
|----------|-------------|----------------|
| High | 3 | 3 |
| Medium | 2 | 2 |
| Low | 0 | 0 |
| **Total** | **5** | **5** |

All 19 catalog smells were checked. 14 came back clean — the suite has solid fundamentals (proper `[TestInitialize]`/`[TestCleanup]` lifecycle, no Mystery Guest thanks to in-memory SQLite, no Sensitive Equality, no Redundant Assertions, no Default Test names, no Constructor Initialization, and all fixture fields are used by every test).

---

## Findings by Severity

### HIGH ① — Sleepy Test

**Catalog ref:** testsmells.org #3 — *Sleepy Test*
**Location:** `NotifyOnInsert_SendsEventAfterDelay` (line 87)

```csharp
Thread.Sleep(3000); // 3-second hard wait
```

**Integration-test calibration:** Even for integration tests, `Thread.Sleep` is a smell. It makes the suite 3 s slower per run and is timing-sensitive — it can still fail if the system is under load, or waste time when the event fires in 50 ms.

**Fix — poll with a timeout:**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public async Task NotifyOnInsert_SendsEventAfterDelay()
{
    var user = new User("dave@example.com", "Dave");
    _repository.Insert(user);

    // Poll up to 5 s, checking every 100 ms
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
    while (!_repository.WasNotificationSent(user.Id))
    {
        await Task.Delay(100, cts.Token);
    }

    Assert.IsTrue(_repository.WasNotificationSent(user.Id));
}
```

**Risk if unfixed:** Flaky CI failures and artificially slow test suite (Camara et al. SAST 2021 correlate Sleepy Test with flakiness).

---

### HIGH ② — Conditional Test Logic

**Catalog ref:** testsmells.org #1 — *Conditional Test Logic*
**Location:** `GetUser_ReturnsCorrectType` (lines 101-108)

```csharp
if (loaded is PremiumUser premium)
{
    Assert.IsTrue(premium.DiscountRate > 0);
}
else
{
    Assert.AreEqual("Eve", loaded!.Name);
}
```

One branch is **never exercised** (a `User("Eve")` is inserted — the `PremiumUser` branch is dead code). This hides a testing gap: the discount-rate behavior is *never* verified.

**Fix — split into two explicit tests:**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetUser_StandardUser_ReturnsCorrectName()
{
    _repository.Insert(new User("eve@example.com", "Eve"));
    var loaded = _repository.GetByEmail("eve@example.com");

    Assert.IsNotNull(loaded);
    Assert.AreEqual("Eve", loaded.Name);
}

[TestMethod]
public void GetUser_PremiumUser_HasPositiveDiscount()
{
    _repository.Insert(new PremiumUser("vip@example.com", "Vera", discountRate: 0.15));
    var loaded = (PremiumUser)_repository.GetByEmail("vip@example.com")!;

    Assert.IsTrue(loaded.DiscountRate > 0);
}
```

**Risk if unfixed:** Hidden gap — the `PremiumUser` path looks covered but is never reached.

---

### HIGH ③ — Assertion-Free Test (Unknown Test)

**Catalog ref:** testsmells.org #4 — *Unknown Test / Empty Test*
**Location:** `BulkInsert_RunsWithoutErrors` (lines 113-119)

```csharp
public void BulkInsert_RunsWithoutErrors()
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++)
    {
        _repository.Insert(new User($"bulk{i}@example.com", $"Bulk User {i}"));
    }
    // ← no assertion
}
```

The name implies "no exception = pass," but the framework will mark this as **passing even if `Insert` silently drops every row**. This is false confidence.

**Fix — assert the outcome:**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void BulkInsert_PersistsAllRecords()
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++)
    {
        _repository.Insert(new User($"bulk{i}@example.com", $"Bulk User {i}"));
    }

    var users = _repository.ListAll();
    Assert.AreEqual(100, users.Count, "All 100 bulk-inserted users should be persisted.");
}
```

**Risk if unfixed:** Silent data-loss bugs go undetected; coverage numbers inflate without real verification.

---

### MEDIUM ④ — Assertion Roulette

**Catalog ref:** testsmells.org (extended) — *Assertion Roulette*
**Location:** `InsertUser_PersistsToDatabase` (lines 35-38)

```csharp
Assert.IsNotNull(loaded);
Assert.AreEqual("Alice", loaded.Name);
Assert.AreEqual("alice@example.com", loaded.Email);
Assert.IsTrue(loaded.Id > 0);
```

Four assertions, zero descriptive messages. A failure in CI produces output like `Assert.AreEqual failed. Expected:<Alice>. Actual:<alice>` — you must open the source to know *which property* failed.

**Fix — add message parameters:**

```csharp
Assert.IsNotNull(loaded, "User should be retrievable after insert.");
Assert.AreEqual("Alice", loaded.Name, "Name should round-trip.");
Assert.AreEqual("alice@example.com", loaded.Email, "Email should round-trip.");
Assert.IsTrue(loaded.Id > 0, "Auto-generated Id should be positive.");
```

**Risk if unfixed:** Slow failure triage, especially in CI logs without IDE context.

---

### MEDIUM ⑤ — Magic Number Test

**Catalog ref:** testsmells.org #6 — *Magic Number Test*
**Location:** `BulkInsert_RunsWithoutErrors` (line 115) and `NotifyOnInsert_SendsEventAfterDelay` (line 87)

```csharp
for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++)   // Why 100? Boundary? Stress threshold?
Thread.Sleep(3000);              // Why 3000 ms?
```

**Calibration:** The `3` in `Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)` (line 76) and `10` in `Assert.AreEqual(10, users.Count)` (line 132) are *contextually self-documenting* (items were added just above) — **not flagged**.

**Fix — use named constants:**

```csharp
private const int BulkInsertBatchSize = 100;
// ...
for (int i = 0; i < BulkInsertBatchSize; i++)
```

**Risk if unfixed:** Unclear test intent; reviewers can't tell if 100 is a meaningful boundary or arbitrary.

---

## Smell-Free Patterns ✅

These tests are well-structured — worth highlighting as examples:

| Test | Why it's clean |
|------|---------------|
| `InsertUser_PersistsToDatabase` | Clear arrange-act-assert, verifies multiple facets (apart from missing messages) |
| `UpdateUser_ModifiesExistingRecord` | Focused: one mutation, one verification |
| `DeleteUser_RemovesFromDatabase` | Clean negative assertion (`Assert.IsNull`) |
| `ListUsers_ReturnsAllInserted` | Good use of `CollectionAssert`; count is self-documenting |
| `InsertUser_ConcurrentInserts_MaintainsIntegrity` | Genuine concurrency integration test with a meaningful assertion |

The class also correctly uses `[TestInitialize]`/`[TestCleanup]` (no *Constructor Initialization* smell) and in-memory SQLite (no *Mystery Guest* or *Resource Optimism*).

---

## Prioritized Remediation Plan

| Priority | Smell | Fix | Effort |
|----------|-------|-----|--------|
| 🔴 1 | **Assertion-Free Test** — `BulkInsert_RunsWithoutErrors` | Add `Assert.AreEqual(100, users.Count)` | ~2 min |
| 🔴 2 | **Conditional Test Logic** — `GetUser_ReturnsCorrectType` | Split into two focused tests | ~5 min |
| 🔴 3 | **Sleepy Test** — `NotifyOnInsert_SendsEventAfterDelay` | Replace `Thread.Sleep` with async polling | ~10 min |
| 🟡 4 | **Assertion Roulette** — `InsertUser_PersistsToDatabase` | Add message strings to each `Assert` | ~2 min |
| 🟡 5 | **Magic Number Test** — bulk loop & sleep literals | Extract named constants | ~2 min |

Start with **#1** — it's the highest-risk/lowest-effort fix (a passing test that verifies nothing is worse than no test at all).
